(28 Oct 1997) T/I:   10:46:58
A court hearing which will affect the future of the Church of Scientology in Germany began in Berlin on Tuesday (28/10). The Federal Administrative Court was considering the legal status of an organisation which is part of the sect. The eventual verdict should determine if Scientology can be considered a religion in Germany.
At issue is whether the organisation is a church, and therefore exempt from taxes under German law, or a business.
SHOWS:
BERLIN, GERMANY, 28/10
VS people entering the Federal Administrative Court;
Lawyers talking about the case;
inside court;
people waiting;
The five Federal Administrative Court judges entering the room;
judges taking a seat;
CA press;
PAN from press to judges;
MS judges;
people entering the room;
SOT Michael Quaas, lawyer for the state of Baden-Wuerttenberg, (in German): "It's a business society not a church. This court case is simply a question of whether the Church of Scientology is a church or a building society. For us it is clear they are a business society. The law clear states that only churches don't have to pay taxes....the
scientologists are a business.";
CA audience waiting;
1.28

